observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the

(a) City Budget Officer and the CGM Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer to maximize the utilization of idle Disaster Funds under the DRRMF before resorting to any augmentation of fund in order not to sacrifice the PPAs under the 20% DF;

(b) BAC to indicate the required technical specifications involving the acquisition of the desired type or nature of the goods in the POs and Contracts; and

(c) City Accountant to

(i) support with sufficient and appropriate documentation all transactions prior to payment;

(ii) adjust the balances of the accounts Advances to Officers and Employees and Advances to SDO to correct the misclassification of accounts in the recording of cash advances;

(iii) cause the immediate submission of the unsubmitted paid DVs totaling to ₱1,920,585.25 to the Audit Team; and

(iv) strictly adhere to the submission to the Audit Team of DVs and their supporting documents within ten days of the ensuing month.

We recommended  that the LCE as head of the CMDC, hand in hand with the CPDO, ensure that

(a) the priority development projects are specifically identified in the AIP through thorough and regular discussion with other sectoral members of the CMDC;

(b) the APP is  prepared for infrastructure projects;



(c) a realistic time-frame is set for their implementation; and

(d) public bidding as a mode of procurement is adopted for a smooth implementation of projects according to the Plan.

We also recommended that the BAC Secretariat and City Engineering Office take note of the deficiencies noted in the posting of signboard for information to the general public of ongoing project, and the requirements of the 2016 IRR of RA No. 9184 be religiously complied with to ensure the promotion of transparency, competitiveness, integrity and quality of projects implemented by the City.

We recommended that the LCE

(a) investigate the incurrence of negative slippage on several development projects, and take appropriate action to hold liable the City officials concerned, and contractors for the delay;

(b) require the City Engineer to request from the contractors concerned a Statement of Work Accomplished, furnished the Audit Team;

(c) require the BAC Secretariat 

(i)  to forward to the Audit Team the lacking documents; and 

(ii)henceforth, submit the perfected contract together with its integral parts within five days from its signing; and

(d) require the City Engineering Office (CEO) to

(i) exercise regular monitoring of ongoing projects to enforce the completion of the projects on time; 

(ii) strictly observe the posting of billboards on ongoing projects for transparency and public information; and

(iii) seek the assistance of the officials of the barangay concerned to  keep an eye on the signboards to prevent them from being stolen. If warranted, impose penalty on takers of the signboard.

We recommended  that the LCE support the advocacies of RA No. 9003 by

(a) ensuring to make the City MRF fully functional and environmental friendly through established concrete and long-term programs, project and activities to promote waste reduction, recycling, composting, and waste processing in an environmentally sound manner;

(b) utilizing the available machineries and keep them intact and in good condition to avoid manual processing of wastes;

(c) continuing the education campaign on proper waste management and disposal to all component barangays; and

(d) conducting regular meetings with component barangays, and different stakeholders to tackle the current status of the City's compliance with RA No. 9003 and come up with coordinated projects to address the common concerns on solid waste management.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the City Accounting Office (CAO) to 

(a) update and adjust the books relative to the (i) reversion to the Cash in Bank account and reversion to the payable or government equity the stale checks of ₱116,045.54; 

(ii) closing of the Postal Bank account and transfer of its cash balance to the Land Bank of the Philippines (LBP) under the Trust Fund (TF) Proper; and 

(iii) recorded Development Bank of the Philippines (DBP) account with reported balance of ₱15,760.35 but no records at the City Treasurer’s Office (CTO);  

(b) record in the books the deposit made to SEF account totaling ₱367,961.99; 

(c) record check disbursements based on the Report of Checks Issued (RCI) submitted by the CTO. If unclaimed or unreleased checks were recorded in the books, indicate the same for adjustment of the cash in bank balance at year-end; and 




(d) henceforth, monitor closely the preparation of the bank reconciliation statements to effect any adjustments in the books in a timely fashion.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the CAO to 
(a) comply with the prescribed accounting entries in the transfer and utilization of the LDRRMF in accordance with PPSAS; 

(b)  record the unexpended balances of the CYs 2017 and 2018 to the TL- LDRRMF totaling ₱44,398,607.50; 

(c) revert the TL-LDRRMF, aged more than five years aggregating to ₱78,201,514.02  to the unappropriated surplus of the GF; and 

(d) adjust  the entry made for the amount transferred to GF amounting to ₱10,094,749.39 in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009.

We recommended that the LCE (a) revisit the terms and conditions of the MOA signed by and between the City and the DSWD to be properly guided by the obligations of the City in the implementation of the SFP; 

(b) open a separate trust fund account for the SFP;

(c) require the CSWDO, GSO, CTO, CAO and the Parents –Teachers of the day care children to convene and evaluate the need to implement the SFP through cash advance to be used for the purchase of food items in accordance with the menu provided by the DSWD;  

(d) require the GSO and the CSWDO to account for actual delivered items to day care centers by the Supplier prior to full payment; 

(e) consider refraining from sourcing rice and food items from Suppliers other than the NFA; and 

(f) strictly abide by the laws, rules and regulations on posting of public information relating to PPA, pursuant to COA Circular 2013-004.

We recommended that the LCE require the City Human Resource Management Officer: (a) prepare and issue a policy guideline on the screening and recruitment of JO personnel;

(b) prepare a contract of service signed by and between the City and the JO detailing therein the works to be done, duration of the contract, rate per day, immediate supervisor, among others; 

(c)  require the JO to submit their quantified accomplishment report for the period signed by their immediate supervisor; and 

(d) refrain from assigning the JOs to sensitive functions such as custodian of funds, collecting functions, and assignments that would duplicate the works of regular employees.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE (a) require the  CAO  to prepare an aging of cash advances for monitoring of cash advances and issue demand letters to accountable officers to compel them to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances;

(b) refrain from granting cash advances to employees not designated as Special Disbursing Officers (SDOs);  

(c) assess if there is a need to  increase the maximum cash accountability of DOs to cover the amount of their cash advances;  

(d)  require the CAO to coordinate with the City Agriculture to (i) identify the grantees; (ii) monitor their payments; and (iii) recover the collectibles to sustain the program for other City constituents.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE (a)  require the CAO to recognize inventories as asset at the time of purchase, and expense based on the monthly issuance reports;

(b) require the General Services Office (GSO) to instruct the operating units such as the Rural Health Units (RHUs) and Division Office of the Department of Education to prepare  the corresponding control documents such as Request Issuance Slip (RIS), Monthly reports of receipt and issue of  stocks; stocks cards and other property records for proper accountability and monitoring; 

(c) require the GSO to ensure  that all procurements/deliveries pass through rigid inspection and acceptance  prior to release to implementing units including that of the SEF-funded procurement; 

(d)  require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and the GSO to comply with the posting requirement in the PhilGEPS and in three conspicuous places for small value procurement; and


(e) comply with the required documentation of procurement of   drugs and medicines pursuant to  Food and Drug Administration (FDA) Act of 2009   and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

We recommended that the LCE (a) require the GSO, CAO, City Assessors Officer, and City Legal Office to further exert their coordinated efforts in ensuring that the parcels of land acquired by the City through purchase or donation are titled and recognized  in the books based on the fair value or acquisition cost to reflect the true financial condition of the City; 

(b) require the City Engineering Office to forward a copy of the inspection and acceptance documents on completed public infrastructure projects  for listing at the GSO;  



(c) ensure that the Offices of the GSO and CAO are adequately manned in order that said Offices could substantially accomplish their tasks in the PPE recording, documentation, monitoring, inventory taking, reporting, and reconciliation of records;  and 

(d) require the CAO to effect the necessary adjustments on the Land, Road Networks, depreciation, and derecognition of PPE accounts.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the CAO to (a) strictly follow the relevant rules and regulations prescribing the timely remittance of withheld Pag-IBIG, PhilHealth, and GSIS contributions; 

(b) explain the occurrence of discrepancies in the GL records vis-à-vis actual amount withheld and settle the discrepancies noted; and 

(c) closely monitor said accounts by conducting monthly reconciliation between the recognized withheld amounts and the remittances made.

We recommended that the Local School Board chair (a) call for a frequent meeting with the members of the LSB to tackle the relevant and critical issues in the education system in the public sector, and in coordinated efforts, plan the allocation of the SEF largely on the priority projects enumerated under JC No. 01; 

(b) submit to the DepEd Regional Office the research output undertaken by the DepEd Division personnel as an input to the Department’s sharing and use of research results; 

(c) set a budget limit for every activity and project of the DepED such as CLRAA, City Meet and Palarong Pambansa as contained in the project proposal approved by the authorized personnel of the LSB; 

(d) refrain from allowing the grant of cash advance without the supporting approved project proposal as a medium in determining how the cash advances are to be expended; and 

(e) submit an explanation on the unlocated LCD projectors aggregating to ₱799,000.00.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) reconstitute the City Social Wastes Management Board (CSWMB) to include representatives from a non-government organization, manufacturing industry, recycling industry, and concerned government agencies; and monitor the implementation of various ordinances made by the Sangguniang Panglungsod in connection with solid waste management for strict enforcement.

We also recommended that the LCE as chairman of the CSWB (a) convene a meeting to tackle 
the current status of the City's compliance with R.A. 9003;

(b) instruct the Human Resource Department to look into the lack of personnel at the City Economic and Natural Resources Office (CENRO) for the latter to properly perform and accomplish its functions; 


(c) fortify the "Abot Kamay" program by advocating that all Barangays undergo the lectures and workshops; 

(d) require the concerned offices to report on the status of the Malolos Ecopark project, Material Recovery Facility, and the Solid Waste Management Plan and other existing programs/projects/activities on solid waste management;  

(e) assign a point person that will facilitate the revisions needed in the ten-year Solid Waste Management Plan; and 

(f) discuss with the Board the adoption of waste reduction programs.

We recommended that the LDRRMC (a) monitor and review the progress and challenges in the implementation of the Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Plan and to develop an elaborate action plan to ensure the fulfillment of programmed PPAs; 

(b) convene frequently or as necessary in order to formulate programs, projects and activities for the previous years’ unexpended LDRRMF; 

(c) comply with the Disaster Preparedness Minimum Standards to strengthen the capacities to anticipate, cope and recover from negative impacts of any catastrophe; and 

(d) consider the construction of evacuation centers suitable for temporary habitation of the displaced families in times of calamities as required by RA No. 10121.

We also recommended that the City Accounting Office and City Budget Officer maintain the prescribed registries in the utilization of LDRRMF.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 
(a) convene the LDC hand in hand with the City Planning Development Office to identify specifically the development projects to be prioritized and implemented during the year to ensure timely implementation of projects; 

(b) create a monitoring team who shall be tasked to evaluate and monitor the implementation of planned projects; 

(c) require the City Engineer’s Office to (i) refrain from implementing projects “By Administration” in the absence of the City’s equipment in carrying out the project; 

(ii) submit to the Audit Team the perfected contract within five days from signing together with its integral parts for timely contract review; and

 (iii) observe the provision on full disclosure of implemented projects through appropriate posting of billboard/information.

We recommended that the LCE (a) make a representation with the Sanggunian Panglungsod to enact ordinances to upgrade the LCR, GRPA, and Market Code to improve the City’s revenue performance and cope up with the rising cost of governance; 

(b) in the absence of the upgraded tax rates and regulatory fees, (i) set a realistic forecast of revenue based on the actual collections made in the previous years to avoid budget and cash overdraft; 

(ii) require the CEEDO and the City Treasurer’s Office to maintain individual stallholders’ ledger cards wherein rental payments are posted; and 

(iii) prepare monthly collection reports from market stallholders to ensure appropriate monitoring and accounting; and 

(c) require the City Accounting Office to maintain special accounts for market and other economic enterprises to determine their financial condition and results of operations.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) create inventory committee to facilitate the completion of the inventory taking for all their properties and the preparation and submission of the corresponding report thereof;

(b) require the City Accountant and the CGSO to maintain and update their respective property records and regularly reconcile them; 



(c) create disposal committee to take appropriate action for the disposition of unserviceable properties; and



d) require the City Accountant to prepare the necessary lapsing schedule to support the computation for depreciation for all their depreciable properties.

We recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee and other concerned officials and personnel of the City to:

(a) strictly comply with the Government Procurement Reform Act or the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and Section 7(a) of RA No. 6713; 


(b) refrain from granting food assistance to unqualified beneficiaries and  resorting to  unnecessary spending of government funds and; 

(c) desist from making expenditures that are not supported by available appropriations.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Accounting Office, GSO and Inventory Committee, as the case may be, 
(a) mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items; 

(b) prepare and maintain property ledger cards and schedules for the PPE; 

(c) strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results;

(d) dispose the unserviceable assets to avoid further deterioration; and 

(e) set up a spreadsheet application or lapsing schedule for the PPE items to facilitate the computation for the periodic depreciation for each PPE item.

We recommended that Management 

(a) refrain from paying unbooked prior year’s obligations against current year’s appropriation; 

(b) instruct the City Accountant to observe the accrual method of accounting  to assure that valid obligations are recognized as expenses within the period of incurrence; 

(c) instruct the General Services Officer and/or official concerned   to immediately cause the repair of the bulldozer owned by the City to save on rental expenses; 

(d) include in the annual budget the appropriation for a new bulldozer to avoid the incurrence of unreasonable rent expenses and avail the prolong and efficient use of a new equipment.

We recommended that Members of the Provincial Local School Board:
a. prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;
b. request for inputs from the DepEd official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund; 
c. maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprogramming, if necessary; and
d. comply with DepEd Order No. 44 and stop the procurement of instructional materials until the issuance is revoked to avoid suspensions/disallowances in audit.

We reiterated our recommendations  that the Local Chief Executive promulgate policies on subscription or set of controls that justifies the reasonableness and necessity of entering into subscription contracts of mobile phones and clearly defines and assigns, among others, the 

(a) authority to bind the City in the subscription contract;

(b) limitation on the usage or consumption of mobile phones; 

(c) person entitled to the plan; 

(d) obligations of the plan holder on accession and accessories derived from the contracts or plans; and 

(e) office or officer in charge of monitoring and ensuring proper implementation of the policy.
